{{For|the social group of people in Rajasthan and Gujarat|Lodha}} {{Infobox Ethnic group |group = Lodha |image = |pop = |region1 = {{flag|India}} |region2 = {{spaces|14}}[[West Bengal]] |pop2 = 84,966 |region3 = {{spaces|13}} [[Orissa, India|Orissa]] |pop3 = |languages = [[Lodhi language|Lodhi]] |religions = |related =[[Munda people]] {{•}} [[Sabar (people)|Sabar]] {{•}} [[Lodha Muslims]] }}
'''Lodha people''' are a [[Tribe|tribal]]/[[Adivasi]] people living primarily in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|states]] of [[West Bengal]] and [[Odisha]], mostly in the [[Paschim Medinipur district]]. A section of the Lodha has converted to [[Islam]], and form a distinct community of [[Lodha Muslims]].
==Demographics== As per 2001 census, Lodhas numbered 84,966 and formed 1.9 per cent of the [[Scheduled castes and scheduled tribes|scheduled tribe]] population of West Bengal. They had a literacy rate of 34.8 per cent.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/Tables_Published/SCST/dh_st_westbengal.pdf |title = West Bengal: Data Highlights the Scheduled Tribes| accessdate = 2009-09-26 | last = | first = | work = Census of India 2001 | publisher = Census Commission of India }}</ref>
They are found in Suliapada and Morada blocks of Baripada sub-division of Mayurbhanj district of Orissa.<ref>{{cite web |url =http://mayurbhanj.nic.in/tribe.htm |title = Mayurbhanj, Tribal languages, festivals and culture| accessdate = 2009-09-26 | last = | first = | work = | publisher = }}</ref>
==Focus== Lodha means piece of flesh named after their ancestor. Lodhas have been in the focus of anthropologists and social activists.<ref>{{cite book |url =https://books.google.com/books?id=c3TqmBoQnf4C&pg=PA219&lpg=PA219&dq=Lodha+tribe&source=bl&ots=0e2jSnjzjq&sig=MAFci03IbywPX69VpeiLNuoPcBk&hl=en&ei=s77ASrXfMNPL8QbV2oTAAQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=3#v=onepage&q=Lodha%20tribe&f=false |title = Rise of anthropology in India: a social science orientation, Volume 1 By Lalita Prasad Vidyarthi | accessdate = 2009-09-26 | last = | first = | work = | publisher = }}</ref> During the early period of their rule, the British government in India oppressed the tribal people of [[Jungle Mahals]], who were traditionally dependent upon the forests for a living. They had revolted but were ruthlessly suppressed. Having been deprived of their livelihood and without any alternatives, they took to criminal ways of life and were subsequently branded a criminal tribe. They should properly be labelled as uprooted rebels. Lodha titles are Nayek, Mallick, Digar, Sardar, Bhokta, Kotal, Dandapat, Bhunya etc. These titles. [[Sabar (people)|Sabars]].<ref>Ghosh, Binoy, ''Paschim Banger Sanskriti'', (in Bengali), part I, 1976 edition, pp. 201-203, Prakash Bhaban</ref> One of the most important research on the Lodhas was done by a Calcutta University faculty, Professor Probodh Kumar Bhowmick<ref>Rehabilitation of a 'Denotified Community': The Ex-Criminal Lodhas of West Bengal, Royal Anthropological Institute Newsletter No. 44 (Jun., 1981), pp. 6-8, https://www.jstor.org/stable/3032233</ref><ref>Lodhas of West Bengal: A Socio-economic Study by P.K.Bhowmick https://www.amazon.com/Lodhas-Bengal-Socio-Economic-Study-Foreword/dp/B000OMQZYY</ref> Much later, researchers from the Department of Anthropology at Vidyasagar University have done empirical studies on the development scenario of the Lodha tribe in Midnapore district<ref>https://www.academia.edu/7999059/Lodhas_of_West_Bengal_A_Case_Study</ref><ref>https://www.researchgate.net/publication/257221844_Ground_realities_of_Development_among_the_Lodhas_in_West_Bengal</ref> who were by that time declared as a 'Primitive Tribal Group'(PTG) by the Government of India.
