{{distinguish|Piro Pueblo language}} {{Infobox language |name=Piro |nativename=Piro |pronunciation={{IPA-xx|ˈjine|}} |states=[[Peru]] |ethnicity=[[Yine people]], [[Manchineri]] |speakers={{sigfig|5,080|1}}<!--data only supports 1 sig fig--> |date=2000–2004 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Southern |fam3=[[Piro languages|Piro]] |lc1=pib|ld1=Yine |lc2=mpd|ld2=Machinere (Manitenére) |glotto=yine1238 |glottoname=Yine |glotto2=mach1268 |glottoname2=Machinere }}
'''Piro''' is a [[Maipurean language]] spoken in [[Peru]]. It belongs to the Piro group which also includes [[Iñapari]] (†) and [[Apurinã language|Apurinã]]. The principal variety is '''Yine'''. The [[Manchineri]] who live in [[Brazil]] ([[Acre (state)|Acre]]) and reportedly also in [[Bolivia]] speak what may be a dialect of Yine (Aikhenvald, Kaufman). A vocabulary labeled ''Canamaré'' is "so close to Piro [Yine] as to count as Piro", but has been a cause of confusion with the unrelated [[Kanamarí language]].<ref>Harald Hammarström (2013) ''Review of the Ethnologue, 16th Ed.''</ref>
This language is also called Contaquiro, Pira, Piro, Pirro, Simiranch, or Simirinche. ''Cushichineri'' has been reported as a language, but is actually a family name used with Whites (Matteson 1965). The name ''Mashco'' has sometimes been incorrectly applied to the Yine. (See [[Mashco Piro language|Mashco Piro]].)
As of 2000, essentially all of the 4,000 ethnic [[Yine people]] speak the language. They live in the [[Ucayali Department|Ucayali]] and [[Cusco Department]]s, near the [[Ucayali River]], and near the [[Madre de Dios River]] in the [[Madre de Dio Region]] in [[Peru]]. Literacy is comparatively high. A dictionary has been published in the language and the language is taught alongside [[Spanish language|Spanish]] in some Yine schools. There are also a thousand speakers of Machinere.<ref name="e18"/>
Piro has an [[active–stative]] syntax.<ref>Aikhenvald, "Arawak", in Dixon & Aikhenvald, eds., ''The Amazonian Languages'', 1999.</ref>
